    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">1. Google Business Profile (complete, verified, active)</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Your Google Business Profile is the single most important factor for Gemini visibility on local queries. Gemini pulls business name, category, hours, services, photos and posts directly from GBP. A verified, complete profile gives Gemini structured, trusted data to work with. An incomplete one gives it reasons to recommend someone else.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Verify your GBP if you have not already. Complete every field: categories, services, business description, hours, attributes.</li>
      <li>Add at least 10 high-quality photos. Include exterior, interior, team and work shots.</li>
      <li>Post to GBP at least twice a month. Updates, offers and events all count.</li>
      <li>Add your products or services with descriptions. Gemini uses these when matching queries to businesses.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Gemini weighs GBP data more heavily than any other AI platform because it has direct access to Google's business data layer. ChatGPT and Perplexity have to infer this information from web pages.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">2. Google Reviews (volume + recency)</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Gemini reads Google Reviews when deciding which businesses to recommend. It considers overall rating, number of reviews, how recent they are, and what customers say. A business with 200 reviews averaging 4.7 stars will consistently outperform one with 12 reviews at 4.9. Volume and recency matter more than a perfect score.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Build a consistent review generation process. Ask every customer, not just the happy ones.</li>
      <li>Respond to every review within 48 hours. Gemini can see response patterns.</li>
      <li>Encourage detailed reviews that mention specific services. "Great accountant for small business tax returns" gives Gemini more to work with than "Great service."</li>
      <li>Do not buy reviews or use review gating. Google detects this and it damages your profile.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Gemini synthesises review sentiment into its recommendations. It does not just count stars. It reads the text and understands what customers praise and criticise.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">3. Schema markup (LocalBusiness, FAQPage, Article)</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Schema markup gives Gemini structured data it can parse without interpretation. LocalBusiness schema tells it exactly what you do, where you are, and when you are open. FAQPage schema feeds question-and-answer pairs directly into its knowledge. Article schema with author, date and topic helps it assess content quality and freshness.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Implement LocalBusiness schema on your homepage and contact page with full NAP details, opening hours and service area.</li>
      <li>Add FAQPage schema to any page with questions and answers. This is one of the fastest routes to Gemini citations.</li>
      <li>Use Article schema on blog posts with author name, publication date and last modified date.</li>
      <li>Test all schema with Google's Rich Results Test. Invalid schema is worse than no schema.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Because Gemini operates within Google's ecosystem, it has native access to the structured data Google has already processed. This is a direct pipeline that other AI platforms lack.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">4. Entity clarity across Google ecosystem</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Gemini cross-references your presence across Google Search, Google Maps, Knowledge Graph and Google Business Profile. If your business name appears differently across these, or if your address does not match, Gemini loses confidence in your entity. A strong, consistent entity signal is the foundation of Gemini trust.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Ensure your business name is identical on your website, GBP, Google Maps, and all directory listings.</li>
      <li>Use the same address format everywhere. Do not abbreviate "Road" on one listing and spell it out on another.</li>
      <li>Link your website to your GBP. Add your GBP link to your website footer.</li>
      <li>If you have a Knowledge Panel, check it for accuracy. Use Google's claim process to correct errors.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> At Rank4AI, entity clarity is one of the first things we check in an audit. Gemini is the most sensitive AI platform to entity inconsistencies because it has the most data sources to cross-reference.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">5. Answer-first content with clear headings</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Gemini extracts answers from content that is structured clearly. It looks for a question in the heading, followed immediately by a direct answer. Content that buries the answer after three paragraphs of introduction gets skipped. The pattern is simple: ask the question, answer it, then expand.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Structure content with clear H2 headings that reflect real questions your audience asks.</li>
      <li>Put the answer in the first sentence after each heading. Expand with detail below.</li>
      <li>Use short paragraphs. Gemini parses shorter blocks more effectively than dense walls of text.</li>
      <li>Include lists and tables where appropriate. Structured formats give Gemini clean data to extract.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Gemini's extraction engine is built on the same technology that powers Google's Featured Snippets. If your content already wins Featured Snippets, it is well positioned for Gemini citations.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">6. Authoritative backlinks from known sources</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Gemini inherits Google's understanding of authority. Backlinks from recognised industry publications, government sites, educational institutions and established media outlets tell Google your site is a trusted source. Gemini uses this trust signal when deciding which sources to cite in its responses.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Focus on earning links from sites Google already trusts: industry bodies, trade associations, established news outlets.</li>
      <li>Publish original research or data that others want to reference. This generates natural backlinks.</li>
      <li>Contribute expert commentary to journalists via platforms like HARO, Qwoted or Response Source.</li>
      <li>Avoid low-quality link building. Gemini benefits from the same authority signals that help Google rankings.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Unlike ChatGPT, which uses Bing's index, Gemini uses Google's own authority metrics. Your Google Search authority translates directly to Gemini visibility.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">7. Wikipedia and Wikidata presence</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Google's Knowledge Graph draws heavily from Wikipedia and Wikidata. If your business or its founder has a verified Wikipedia entry, Gemini treats that entity as established and notable. This is particularly powerful for businesses in competitive sectors where Gemini needs to choose between similar options.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Check if your business meets Wikipedia's notability guidelines before attempting an article.</li>
      <li>Create or update your Wikidata entry with accurate structured data: founding date, industry, headquarters, founders.</li>
      <li>Ensure your Wikipedia references are from independent, reliable sources. Self-published sources do not count.</li>
      <li>If a full Wikipedia article is not achievable, focus on being mentioned in relevant industry or topic articles.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> A Wikidata entry is the fastest route to a Google Knowledge Panel, which in turn is one of the strongest signals Gemini uses to validate an entity.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">8. Consistent NAP across directories</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Name, Address and Phone number consistency across the web reinforces your entity in Google's systems. When Gemini encounters the same business details on your website, GBP, Yell, Thomson Local, industry directories and social profiles, it builds confidence. When details conflict, confidence drops.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Audit your top 20 directory listings for NAP accuracy. Fix any that are outdated or incorrect.</li>
      <li>Use the exact same business name format everywhere. No abbreviations on some and full names on others.</li>
      <li>Include your phone number in the same format across all listings. Choose either spaces or no spaces and stick with it.</li>
      <li>Remove duplicate listings on the same directory. Duplicates confuse entity resolution.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Google aggregates directory data into its own systems. Inconsistent NAP does not just affect individual directories. It weakens your entity across everything Google powers, including Gemini.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">9. Regular content publishing</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">Gemini favours sources that demonstrate ongoing activity. A website that publishes regularly signals a live, engaged business. A site where the last blog post is from 2024 signals a business that may have gone dormant. Freshness is not just about recency. It is about consistency.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Publish at least two pieces of content per month. Blog posts, case studies, guides or industry commentary all count.</li>
      <li>Update existing content when information changes. Add a "last updated" date to signal freshness.</li>
      <li>Cover topics your audience actually searches for. Use Google Search Console to find queries where you appear but do not rank well.</li>
      <li>Maintain a content calendar to ensure consistency. Sporadic publishing is only slightly better than no publishing.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Gemini can see when your content was last crawled by Google. Regular publishing keeps your site in Google's active crawl queue, which keeps your content fresh in Gemini's knowledge.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-12 mb-4">10. Video content on YouTube</h2>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5">YouTube is Google's own video platform, and Gemini has direct access to its content. Videos with clear titles, detailed descriptions and proper tags feed into Gemini's knowledge base. For businesses in sectors where video works well (trades, professional services, education), YouTube is an underused advantage.</p>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>What to do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-3">
      <li>Create videos that answer common questions in your industry. Keep them focused and under 10 minutes.</li>
      <li>Write detailed video descriptions with relevant keywords. Gemini reads descriptions, not just titles.</li>
      <li>Add chapters to longer videos. This helps Gemini extract specific answers from different sections.</li>
      <li>Link your YouTube channel to your website and GBP. This strengthens entity connections across Google's ecosystem.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-5"><strong>Gemini-specific note:</strong> Gemini can reference YouTube content directly in its responses. No other AI platform has this level of integration with a video platform. At Rank4AI, we recommend YouTube as a priority channel for businesses targeting Gemini visibility.</p>

